hands_on_practices.problem:
Consider a linear, static finite element equilibrium system with displacement vector partitioned into boundary and internal degrees of freedom as $\mathbf{u} = \begin{pmatrix} \mathbf{u}_{b} \\ \mathbf{u}_{i} \end{pmatrix}$, stiffness matrix partitioned as
$$
\mathbf{K} \;=\;
\begin{pmatrix}
\mathbf{K}_{bb} & \mathbf{K}_{bi} \\
\mathbf{K}_{ib} & \mathbf{K}_{ii}
\end{pmatrix},
$$
and force vector $\mathbf{f} = \begin{pmatrix} \mathbf{f}_{b} \\ \mathbf{f}_{i} \end{pmatrix}$. The equilibrium equations are
$$
\begin{pmatrix}
\mathbf{K}_{bb} & \mathbf{K}_{bi} \\
\mathbf{K}_{ib} & \mathbf{K}_{ii}
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
\mathbf{u}_{b} \\
\mathbf{u}_{i}
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
\mathbf{f}_{b} \\
\mathbf{f}_{i}
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
Take the specific, symmetric positive definite block data
$$
\mathbf{K}_{bb} \;=\;
\begin{pmatrix}
5.6 & -3 \\
-3  & 10
\end{pmatrix},\qquad
\mathbf{K}_{bi} \;=\;
\begin{pmatrix}
6 \\
0
\end{pmatrix},\qquad
\mathbf{K}_{ii} \;=\; (10),
$$
so that $\mathbf{K}_{ib} = \mathbf{K}_{bi}^{\top}$. Perform static condensation of the internal degree of freedom $\mathbf{u}_{i}$ to obtain the reduced boundary system
$$
\mathbf{S}\,\mathbf{u}_{b} \;=\; \mathbf{f}_{b}^{\star},
$$
where $\mathbf{S}$ is the Schur complement and $\mathbf{f}_{b}^{\star}$ is the condensed right-hand side. Then:

- Compute the reduced stiffness matrix $\mathbf{S}$ explicitly.
- Determine whether $\mathbf{S}$ is strictly diagonally dominant, and state your conclusion.
- Consider the linear stationary Jacobi method applied to $\mathbf{S}\,\mathbf{u}_{b} = \mathbf{f}_{b}^{\star}$. Let $\mathbf{D} = \operatorname{diag}(S_{11}, S_{22})$ and $\mathbf{T}_{J} = \mathbf{I} - \mathbf{D}^{-1}\mathbf{S}$ be the Jacobi iteration matrix. Compute the spectral radius $\rho(\mathbf{T}_{J})$ in exact, closed form.
- Briefly explain, based on your computation and standard convergence theory, whether the loss of strict diagonal dominance due to condensation necessarily prevents convergence of the Jacobi method, and whether the Gauss–Seidel method converges for this reduced system.

Provide your final answer as the exact closed-form expression for $\rho(\mathbf{T}_{J})$. No rounding is required and no units are needed.
